# PDPP — Railway Core deploy target environment block
#
# Operator reference for the variables a managed-platform Core deploy needs.
# Use console.env.example and reference.env.example as the service-specific
# templates. This consolidated block is a readable reference only: some variable
# names intentionally differ per service (`PDPP_RS_URL`, and `PORT` is reference-
# only). It is a subset of `.env.docker.example` (the same variable names and
# meanings); it omits connector credential variables because the first Railway
# Core test runs no browser-backed connector inside the deployed service.
#
# Two application services and one storage backend (see ./README.md):
#   - console   public  (the only internet-reachable origin)
#   - reference private  (Authorization Server + Resource Server)
#   - Postgres  storage  (managed plugin) OR a SQLite file on a mounted volume
#
# `${{...}}` values are Railway reference-variable syntax: Railway substitutes
# them from the named service at deploy time. Do not paste literal secrets into
# committed files.

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Public origin — set on BOTH the console and reference services.
# This is the single internet-reachable HTTPS origin (the console's public
# domain). Composed mode advertises it as the AS issuer and RS resource.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
PDPP_REFERENCE_ORIGIN=https://${{console.RAILWAY_PUBLIC_DOMAIN}}
# Optional: comma-separated extra hostnames permitted as forwarded hosts.
PDPP_TRUSTED_HOSTS=

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# console service (public) — Next.js standalone server.
# Railway injects $PORT; the console binds it. Do not hardcode PORT here.
# The console proxies the full protocol surface to the PRIVATE reference
# service over Railway's private network.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Private internal targets. Bind to the reference service's private domain.
PDPP_AS_URL=http://${{reference.RAILWAY_PRIVATE_DOMAIN}}:7662
PDPP_RS_URL=http://${{reference.RAILWAY_PRIVATE_DOMAIN}}:7663

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# reference service (private) — Authorization Server + Resource Server.
# NOT published as a public origin. The AS 7662 / RS 7663 listeners are
# reachable only over the platform private network.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# The reference image supplies NODE_ENV=production, PORT=7662, AS_PORT=7662,
# RS_PORT=7663, PDPP_REFERENCE_OPERATIONAL_DEFAULTS=1,
# PDPP_RS_URL=http://127.0.0.1:7663, and
# PDPP_EMBEDDING_DOWNLOAD_ALLOWED=0. Keep them out of the pushbutton template so
# they do not become user prompts.

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Owner gate — REQUIRED. A public origin with an empty owner password serves
# the dashboard and device-approval surfaces anonymously. Set a non-empty,
# high-entropy value (e.g. `openssl rand -base64 24`) as a Railway secret.
# The owner-session signing key derives from this value, so a stable password
# keeps owner sessions valid across restarts (there is no separate session
# secret to set). Set on BOTH services.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
PDPP_OWNER_PASSWORD=

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# Storage — choose ONE. The non-durable in-memory / unmounted-SQLite default
# is not a valid configured backend for a deploy that must survive restart.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

# Option A (recommended): managed Postgres. Add the Railway Postgres plugin and
# reference its connection string. Schema bootstraps idempotently at boot — no
# migrate step, no volume. Railway's managed Postgres is plain `postgres`, not
# `pgvector`; the reference falls back to grant-scoped JSONB vector storage,
# which is fine with semantic retrieval off.
PDPP_DATABASE_URL=${{Postgres.DATABASE_URL}}

# Option B: SQLite on a mounted persistent volume. Attach a Railway volume to
# the reference service and point PDPP_DB_PATH onto the mount. The default
# `/var/lib/pdpp/pdpp.sqlite` is NOT under the documented `/root/.pdpp` volume;
# if you leave it at the default and mount elsewhere, data is lost on redeploy.
# Uncomment these and leave PDPP_STORAGE_BACKEND / PDPP_DATABASE_URL above unset.
# PDPP_STORAGE_BACKEND=sqlite
# PDPP_DB_PATH=/data/pdpp.sqlite
